MYCOPLASMA PNEUMONIA, OUTBREAK? - USA (02)
******************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.healthnet.org/programs/promed.html>
See Also
Mycoplasma pneumonia, outbreak? - USA (Kansas): RFI 981116231050
Date: Tue, 17 Nov 1998 08:09:15 -0800
From: Duchin, Jeff <Jeff.Duchin@METROKC.GOV>

In Seattle we are currently investigating an increase in pneumonia among
grade school aged children that appears to be due to _M. pneumoniae_.
Although we have not yet recovered the organism in culture, several cases
have had positive acute mycoplasma IgM titers and there are cases with
bullous myringitis. The clinical picture is characterized by fever, cough
(which may last weeks) and often, pharyngitis, with an incubation period of
2-3 weeks. Although affected individuals have had a clinical response to
new macrolides, the outbreak has been persistent over several months.
There are no recommended effective chemoprophylactic strategies. This may
be due to a combination of factors including the long incubation period and
the persistence of nasopharyngeal carriage after antimicrobial treatment
(at least with older agents). Epidemic mycoplasma pneumonia activity tends
to occur in 4-7 year cycles, my recollection is the last big year was 1993-4.
--
Jeffrey S. Duchin, M.D.
Chief, Communicable Disease Epidemiology
Seattle-King County Dept. of Health
999 3rd Ave, Suite 900, Seattle, WA 98104
Tel: (206) 296-4774 Fax: (206) 296-4803
