Date: Tue, 17 Nov 1998 15:00:28 -0400
From: Jose Luis Ferrero <jferrero@cantv.net>

I am a pediatrician and critical care physician here in Maracaibo. I work
in two 100 bed private hospitals. I have seen many cases as the ones you
describe, but in children all ages. Usually [itstarts like a viral
disease, just like the flu. The patient might not even be coughing, but in
the physical exam you find all kinds of rales, as if there was a huge
pneumonia. Some of them without even slight dyspnea. I immediately treat
them with macrolides with good response. The CXR are usually interstitial
and diffuse, but some are lobar. [The WBC count is low for the CXR
findings, and some even [suggesting viral etiology. Some [patients are
referred by other pediatricians and many different treatments [have been
instituted, but they get to be fine as soon as they start the macrolide. I
am happy to know I am not alone in this.
--
Dr. Jose Luis Ferrero A.
Hospital Clinico
Clinica Falcon
Maracaibo, Venezuela.
e-mail: jferrero@cantv.net
